commit.message: Add LICENSE to MANIFEST.in. Close #86.
Fix format handling so it works with py3.4

Use the new name for `raw_input` in Python 3. Close #82.

Tests don't pass under Python 3 (tried 3.3 and 3.6), but they didn't beforehand either. Hrrm. I wonder how they got into the tox file.

Handle KeyboardInterrupt as nose does.

Merge pull request #70 from ltvolks/master

Gracefully handle proxied SyntaxErrors when using the logcapture plugin
Added comment, explaining why do we pass KeyboardInterrupt silently.

Handle KeyboardInterrupt as nose does.

Original TextTestRunner from nose (https://github.com/nose-devs/nose/blob/master/nose/core.py#L63)
handles KeyboardInterrupt gracefully and runs
all necessary methods like result.printSummary and plugins.finalize.

This patch makes nose-progressive behave like original TextTestRunner.
Fix Exception.message lookup for Py 3.4 compatibility
Add build to .gitignore

Gracefully handle proxied SyntaxErrors when using the logcapture plugin

Fixes erikrose/nose-progressive#62

The logcapture plugin formats errors by extracting and converting
the value to a string. Nose recreates a proxy exception lacking
filename and lineno attributes, which crashes the shortcut formatting
Alternative fix to proper handle line_number format
Fixes template format to handle line_number properly if its None
Update readme for release, and bump version to 1.5.1.
Date copyright back to when the library began.

Tersen licensing stuff a tad.

There's no need to repeat the license info in the readme when it's in the LICENSE file and the trove metadata. Also, set license to simply 'MIT' in setup.py for consistency with my other libraries.
Switch license to MIT; include copy as LICENSE
Avoid a TypeError when running nose-progressive from within `invoke`. Fix #59.

Merge fix for Unicode decoding error when the default encoding isn't UTF-8. FIx #58.

Me and my silly em dashes....
Add a hyphen to 'utf8', just for consistency with how we spell it in tracebacks.py.

read README.rst as UTF-8

This is necessary on Python 3. The default encoding might be ASCII (for
example in a build system) or indeed any encoding other than UTF-8.

Use codecs.open since open doesn't accept an encoding in Python 2.
Talk about clickable URLs in terminals in the readme.
Correct the default editor shortcut template in the readme, after adding hash_if_function.
Add py32 to the tox config, and make sure we test against the 2to3'd source.
Tolerate Nones in traceback components. Fix #56.
Provide for arbitrary customization of the editor shortcut. Drop Python 2.5 support. Bump version to 1.5. Fix #39. Fix #47.
Tweak package short description to be less implementation oriented.
Fix bar not showing up for some suites under Python 3. Bump version to 1.4.3.
